properties.description:
The White House is a contemporary and community art space operated by Create London. Formerly an 18th-century farmhouse, the space was transformed in 2016 by Apparata into a new model for arts engagement.

The White House is currently exhibiting 'Stranger in Silver Walking on Air', an immersive exhibition by Turner Prize-nominated artist Delaine Le Bas, inspired by Roma & Traveller histories.

images.title: Delaine Le Bas' 'Stranger in Silver Walking on Air'. Photography by Alex Christie.
Art-led activity in the White House Front Room
Delaine Le Bas' 'Stranger in Silver Walking on Air'. Photography by Alex Christie.

properties.name: White House, Becontree Estate

properties.description: Early 18th century red brick country home of artist William Hogarth, extended significantly c. 1749-1764. The 2020 extension, funded by the National Lottery Heritage Fund, added the new Weston Studio for learning and activities, and a curved glass wall in the shape of Hogarth's Line of Beauty. Delightful re-landscaped and reinterpreted walled garden containing famous ancient mulberry tree.

images.title: View of the historic house from the walled garden

properties.name: Hogarth's House

properties.description: Grade II-listed Georgian domestic building c.1760, formerly part of the Bedford Estate. Interior refurbished 1925 to form lecture hall (restored 2014), library, bookshop and offices. Oak woodwork and green Doulton tiles line the staircase.

images.title: Bust of Swedenborg by Preston Powers (1879)
Stained glass window image of Swedenborg, vestibule (detail)

properties.name: The Swedenborg Society

properties.description: Early Tudor Palace with Georgian reception rooms, Victorian Chapel, 13 acres of botanic garden and walled garden.

images.title: Previously excavated part of moat at Fulham Palace

properties.name: Fulham Palace

properties.description: Join us for an internal and external tour of RAF Biggin Hill Museum and Chapel. Come along and immerse yourself in the history of Biggin Hill from the establishment of the airfield to the events of the Battle of Britain. Hear stories of the men and women who fought and worked at RAF Biggin Hill.
properties.name: RAF Biggin Hill Museum & Chapel Tour

properties.description: St Mary Abchurch is a unique City church. Unlike almost every church in the City of London it has an almost complete Christopher Wren interior, and it has a painted dome: one of only three Wren domes in the City.

images.title: St Mary Abchurch from Abchurch Lane
The painted dome at St Mary Abchurch

properties.name: St Mary Abchurch

properties.description: A rare example of Thomas Archer's work and a masterpiece of English Baroque, originally dubbed Queen Anne's Footstool. A Grade I listed building, restored by Marshall Sisson after extensive bombing damage, now a busy concert hall.

images.title: The East Side of the Square

properties.name: St John's Smith Square

properties.description: Grade II* listed church with ragstone tower, spire, good stained glass by Kempe and recently restored William Hill organ. A characteristic work of Scott. It is Gothic Revival in the style of the 13C.

images.title: Christ Church Wanstead from the Green

properties.name: Christ Church

properties.description: Grade ll Listed church, that has been much added to over the 800 years of its existence. We have  recently refurbished the organ which has a fine circa 1750s wooden organ case.  The Church has an eight-bell peal still in weekly use– the oldest bell dates from 1680.

images.title: View West of the Organ Case created by Richard Bridge in 1753

properties.name: Parish Church of St Andrew, Enfield

properties.description: During Open House, the Friends of Battersea Parish Church are staging a Floral Festival, organ recitals, historical displays, and on Sunday 14 September at 3pm, a concert by The London Vegetable Orchestra  “Rooted in Culture”: suitable for all ages, King Charles recently tooted a carrot to Twinkle, twinkle! On Friday 19 September at 7pm, author Lamorna Ash will join us for a Q&A and book signing.
properties.name: St Mary's Church, Battersea

properties.description:
An opportunity to visit Crofton Roman Villa and view the archaeological remains of a 10 room house on former Roman farmland, inhabited from 140 AD to 400 AD and the only Roman villa open to the public in greater London!

You can also view the proposed plans and meet the team responsible for the exciting refurbishment works due to take place on the building commencing early 2026.
properties.name: Crofton Roman Villa

properties.description: Well-executed and colourfully detailed example of Victorian reading and vestry rooms (1863) with added public hall by S. Woodridge 1887. Beautiful details inside and out.
properties.name: Isleworth Public Hall

properties.description: A Church of Scotland in London, home to the longest-established Presbyterian congregation in London, worshipping in this location in Covent Garden since 1719. The current building is red brick with Portland stone dressings in a restrained, finely crafted Free Style. Three storeys, recessed slated attic, mullioned and transomed windows. Fine stained glass, most of which is by Farrar Bell.

images.title: Crown Court Church: example of Farrar-Bell stained glass windows.

properties.name: Crown Court Church of Scotland

properties.description: Founded by William the Conqueror's Archbishop Lanfranc in 1080 (the significant crypt survives) St Mary-le-Bow was rebuilt, notably by Wren after the Great Fire and by Laurence King in 1964 after WWII destruction. Home of Bow Bells.

images.title: Sanctuary and nave showing the hanging rood crucifix
The sanctuary; windows by John Hayward
Hanging Rood carved by Otto Irsara, a gift from the people of the Federal Republic of Germany
The current ring of 12 bells dates from 1961
The Blessed Virgin Mary depicted holding the church of St Mary-le-Bow, surrounded by other City churches and their patrons
Wren's Tower viewed from Bow Churchyard

properties.name: St Mary-le-Bow

properties.description: London's main tourist information centre is clad in a specially manufactured system of 220 pre-finished stainless steel panels. The subtly reflective surface provides a striking counterpoint to St Paul's.
properties.name: City Information Centre

properties.description: Pushkin House is an independent arts, cultural and social space. In dialogue with other regions, we focus on the contested legacies, tumultuous present and possible futures of Russian, Eastern European, and post-Soviet geo-cultural spaces. We will be contributing to this year's Open House Festival through a programme of events and initiatives at our Grade-II Listed Building in Bloomsbury Square.

images.title: South facade on Bloomsbury Way. Photo by Dmitri Tsyrenshchikov
Music room. Photo by Dmitri Tsyrenshchikov
Main staircase. Photo by Dmitri Tsyrenshchikov
Entrance hall. Photo by Dmitri Tsyrenshchikov
Pushkin House Bar. Photo by Dmitri Tsyrenshchikov
Pushkin House Bookshop. Photo by Dmitri Tsyrenshchikov

properties.name: Pushkin House

properties.description: St Anne's Church, Kew Green was consecrated in 1714. Built with the support of Queen Anne it has been a place of worship for the Royal Families over the centuries. The original 'chapel' has been extended many times and the church is now a little known gem in South West London with a fascinating past.
properties.name: St Anne's Church, Kew Green

properties.description: Some of London's best Roman remains, comprising late 2C house with a 3C bath house built within its courtyard. First discovered in 1848.
properties.name: Billingsgate Roman House & Baths

properties.description: A £2.6m conversion of an office block into a state-of-the-art theatre with two auditoriums, cafe bar and education studio.

images.title: Audio description touch tour at Park Theatre
Dementia Friendly Programmes at Park Theatre

properties.name: Park Theatre

properties.description: St Anne's Limehouse has been described as 'the finest parish church in England.' Designed by Nicholas Hawksmoor, it is Grade I listed and one of the Major Churches in the Church of England. It is home to a thriving Christian congregation.

images.title: Our exhibition of tapestries made for the Millennium - in our galleries over Open House week

properties.name: St Anne's Church, Limehouse

properties.description: Loughborough Pearson's red brick building is unimposing from the outside, but inside is a riot of Gothic Revival design. Golden mosaics reveal the character of the Grade II* listed chapel, built as part of the Middlesex Hospital.

images.title: The ornate baptisery of the Fitzrovia Chapel

properties.name: Fitzrovia Chapel

properties.description: One of the finest examples of Georgian architecture. It has been hardly altered since built. The church is a rectangular building of Portland stone, with a projecting chancel. Two external walls were restored in 2019. Grade I listed

images.title: Main view of the entrance to St Mary's
The Crypt - full of history, Lord Mayors and Sheriffs
Watchman's Box, memorial to Joseph Wilton RA (G.II listed)
The crypt, accessed through a narrow tunnel, runs the full length of the church
Viewing the Chancel through the eyes of our "there but not there" veterans
The magnificent candelabra in the chancel

properties.name: St Mary The Virgin Wanstead

properties.description: The Stirling-prize shortlisted King’s Cross Masterplan established a framework for the incremental redevelopment of this industrial heritage site through a mix of uses and a network of public spaces structuring new urban blocks and knitting the site into its context.

images.title: Granary Square at King's Cross. Courtesy of John Sturrock and Related Argent
Bagley Walk at King's Cross. Courtesy of John Sturrock and Related Argent

properties.name: King's Cross Masterplan

properties.description: Wren designed building of 1675, interior lost in blitz of 1940, reopened 1957 with 'Wren inspired' interior
properties.name: St Bride's Church, Fleet Street

properties.description: St John at Hackney Church has been Hackney's centre of Christian worship since 1275. The current church was completed in 1792, with major restoration finished in 2020. It's a major ringing centre in East London with ten bells from 4 to 16 cwt - eight from 1957 following the 1955 fire, and two added in 2004. This very active tower rings for Sunday services, national celebrations and commemorations.

images.title: Stained glass window and relief panel in the nave - St John at Hackney
The Altar - St John at Hackney
The Nave - St John at Hackney
The Baptistry - St John at Hackney
The organ and balcony - St John at Hackney
The Nave - St John at Hackney
The North West Stair - St John at Hackney
St John at Hackney bell tower

properties.name: St John at Hackney

properties.description: Our timber-frame building was designed by Matrix Feminist Design Co-Operative, and built by women. It represents our community's history of activism - the same ethos that transformed our site from dereliction into a thriving community garden. At a time when women’s voices were largely excluded from the built environment, Matrix created community spaces with care, collaboration and social purpose.

images.title: Carpenter Louise Heaps working on the building's frame
Louise Heaps (lead carpenter, left) working on the portal frames for the building

properties.name: Walworth Garden

properties.description:
A great little museum set in the Grade 2 listed Ossulston Estate - a prime example of pre-war Social housing - based on Karl Marz Hof in Vienna.
Open Tuesday to Friday 10am-4pm, plus Saturday 13th, Sunday 14th and Saturday 20th September 11am-4pm.

images.title: A museum on the social housing Ossulston Estate - a Space for us?
Pearly Queen outside the People's Museum
Hear the story of stolen social housing art from those who restituted it. Gilbert Bayes 'Draper'

properties.name: People's Museum Somers Town

properties.description:
The building, designed by Mole Architects, comprises a top-lit, 2,000 square foot rehearsal studio, open-plan office, music production studio. 

Constructed entirely from timber, clad in weathered corten steel and designed to limit energy consumption.
properties.name: C2 Clod Ensemble Studios : Design District

properties.description:
A Victorian Church set in a wooded Churchyard, with a vibrant and striking set of Murals around the altar and the Choir.  Beautiful Stained Glass. 
Has indoor toilet facilities. 
A good quality well used organ in good condition, and excellent acoustics.
properties.name: St Mary's Church Bromley

properties.description:
Andaz London Liverpool Street, a concept by Hyatt, blends rich history dating back to the 1200s with modern decor and the vibrant energy of its London neighborhood.

Step inside and join us for an open house tour led by our dedicated team!
properties.name: Andaz London Liverpool Street

properties.description: On the surface Stratford is all Olympics and Westfield: this tour unearths the area's Roman and religious origins, unusual buildings, famous manufacturing pioneers, 20th century hard times and considers (from above) the impacts of its newest quarter.

images.title: Aquatic Centre & Waterworks River: Guide's own photo
Old Stratford Map, credit Newham Archives

properties.name: Stratford: past, present and future

properties.description: Public Tours tours by Architect's DSDHA and the team at National Youth Theatre of the NYT's recently redeveloped RIBA-award-winning building, which created the UK's first theatre dedicated to staging work created by young people. This project is supported by the Mayor of London.

images.title: National Youth Theatre photo by Jim Stephenson
National Youth Theatre Photo by Jim Stephenson

properties.name: National Youth Theatre

properties.description: Morris+Company is an award-winning architecture practice based in Hackney, east London. At our studios on Mare Street, we place the creative ‘act’ of architecture onto the high street, revealing our practice to the public and encouraging engagement with our work and approach. Through our public café, gallery and event spaces we forge meaningful relationships with our local communities.

images.title:
Clay | Culture | Carbon exhibition 
© Sophie Percival

properties.name: Morris+Company / Clay|Culture|Carbon exhibition

properties.description: Woodside Loft is an exceptional loft conversion and was the winner of an SBID International Design Excellence Award (2020). It's part living room, part multi-function space,  part chill-out den, part guest quarters. The conversion makes use of every inch of space and adopts unconventional ideas and solutions to achieve its design objective.
properties.name: Woodside Loft, 4 Singleton Scarp

properties.description: A walk around Brook Green with emphasis on the buried lost river, Stamford Brook.
properties.name: Brook Green walk

properties.description: Holy Innocents Church, South Norwood is a Church of England parish church in the south London suburb of South Norwood, dedicated to the Holy Innocents. It was built in Neo-Gothic imitation of Perpendicular architecture between 1894 and 1895 to designs by the British architect George Frederick Bodley though a planned tower was never built,. The church itself has been Grade II* listed since 1976.

images.title: Side view of Holy Innocents Church, South Norwood
Nave of Holy Innocents Church, South Norwood
Pulpit inside Holy Innocents Church, South Norwood

properties.name: Holy Innocents Church

properties.description: St Anne's Church, a SW London landmark, nicknamed Pepperpot, celebrated its bicentenary in 2024 (Robert Smirke 1824). The church will be open September 15, 17 and 18 for guided tours and exhibits from the archives.
properties.name: St Anne's Church Wandsworth

properties.description: London is the world's first National Park City, and our visitors centre at 80 Mortimer Street is the entry point to hundreds of places to visit and things to do across a greener, healthier and wilder London.

images.title: London National Park City visitors centre at 80 Mortimer Street around the corner from Oxford Circus

properties.name: London National Park City Visitors Centre

properties.description: We are a theatre company for performers and artists with learning disabilities in the West London area. We will put on an exhibition of artworks and costumes at our Community Arts Centre.
properties.name: IMPACT Community Arts Centre

properties.description: A walking tour celebrating the music venues of Camden Town. Learn about the historic bands that have played at the various sites Camden is famous for. From Pink Floyd to Amy Winehouse and beyond. Take a walk on the wild side through Camden's musical highlights.
properties.name: Rock 'n' Roll Camden Tour

properties.description: St Mary's is a Victorian church famous for its second vicar Percy Dearmer who together with Ralph Vaughn Williams produced the English Hymnal in 1906.  We have a rich history of Church Music, beautiful worship and  vestments.  We also have a passion for  social justice within our community.  We were the first parish in Edmonton Diocese to have a woman vicar.
properties.name: St Mary the Virgin Primrose Hill

properties.description: A walking tour of the City, visiting key areas associated with famous writers, from Shakespeare, Dr Johnson, Oscar Wilde, and many others.

images.title: A guide outside Stationer's Hall. Image: Niki Gorick Photography

properties.name: The Literary City

properties.description: A walk around places in the City you might recognise (or not) from the silver screen. Visit the impressive sites used in major films, including Harry Potter, Mission Impossible, James Bond, and many more.

images.title: A guide with Tower Bridge in background. Image: Niki Gorick Photography

properties.name: Film Locations of the City

properties.description: Now part of the Chelsea Heritage Quarter, Chelsea Physic Garden was established in 1673, by the Worshipful Society of Apothecaries of London.  This four-acre green space in the heart of Chelsea is London's oldest botanical garden and home to over 4,500 medicinal, edible and useful plants.

images.title:
A view of the propagation glasshouse at Chelsea Physic Garden

Image credit: Laura Stoner New

properties.name: Chelsea Physic Garden

properties.description: Step into Urbanist Architecture’s private studio in the heart of Greenwich. Explore a space crafted by our interior designers and join our team for insightful talks on tackling Minor Developments in Backland/Infill Sites and navigating the complexities of Green and Grey Belt planning.
properties.name: Urbanist Architecture Studio

properties.description: Marking the 60th anniversary of London’s 32 boroughs, this walking tour explores the evolution of local government through the story of Camberwell. It charts the development of institutions in response to intense social and economic change to shape the city we know today. We will celebrate the visible reminders of this history in the streets around us and ask: why does this matter to Londoners today?

images.title: All's Well, Town Hall - Metropolitan Borough of Camberwell (1934)
Lakanal House, Sceaux Gardens - Metropolitan Borough of Camberwell (1959)
The Pied Piper, Willi Soukop (1957), under the London County Council's Patronage of the Arts Scheme.
Dining and Assembly Hall, Brunswick Park, Stirling and Gowan (1962) - London County Council

properties.name: All's well in Camberwell: walking London's local government history

properties.description: Grade II Listed.   Designed by Adrian Gilbert Scott.  Cruciform shape (120 feet by 120 feet) of steel girder and brick construction. Its Lantern tower – based on Ely Cathedral – is supported on parabolic arches 35 feet wide and 50 feet high.  The Stained Glass Windows were designed by John Wilson of Edinburgh and the Stations of the Cross  carved in Blue Horton Stone by Peter Watts.
properties.name: St Mary & St Joseph Roman Catholic Church, Poplar

properties.description: London based EJM Studio opens its doors during Open House Festival where visitors can take a look behind the scenes to understand how the studio operates.
properties.name: Switchboard Studios, Studio 24

properties.description: Get a sneak peek! Tour the future Newham Heritage Centre at Canning Town Old Library and see the transformation in progress.
properties.name: Hard Hat Tours: Inside Canning Town Old Library

properties.description: Join artist Alisa Ruzavina for an art & ecology walk exploring the diverse land of Regents Park Estate & Regent’s Park through creative exercises, sharing of local stories, plant knowledge & folklore. The walk will include an artist tour of  Wonderscopes – public sculptures celebrating local relationship to changing seasons.
properties.name: Regent’s Park & Estate: Autumn Equinox Exploration

properties.description: Join us at Olympia as we open our doors for the first—and only—time to give the public a behind-the-scenes sneak peek at London's most ambitious transformation. Discover how this iconic landmark is becoming a brand new culture and entertainment destination, as our tour will showcase visitors what's to come.
properties.name: The New Olympia: A Sneak Peek Tour

properties.description: The London Borough of Hounslow is 60!  This exhibition in Hounslow Library explores what the borough looked like in 1965 in terms of architecture and industry, and what life was like for residents then. Contrasting with this, there are contemporary photos showing how our vibrant, diverse and lively borough has changed, with new architecture and life as it is lived now.

images.title: The Chiswick Bus Works photographed in 1967 replaced by Chiswick Business Park.
Chiswick Business Park, that replaced the Bus Works, was completed in 2015.

properties.name: London Borough of Hounslow 60th Anniversary Exhibition
